{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5d0b0d2-01ad-44ca-b486-e40cf4e06d00","content":"No repository-specific docs cover this topic, but here's the general guidance for macOS:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app so the OS writes a core file on crash.\n\n2. **Check `/cores/`** — macOS writes core dumps to `/cores/core.<pid>` by default. Look there after the crash.\n\n3. **Check Apple's Crash Reporter** — macOS also saves crash reports under:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n4. **SIP may block core dumps** — if `/cores/` is empty, System Integrity Protection may be preventing writes. You can verify with `csrutil status`. On dev machines you can disable it (requires recovery mode), or redirect cores via `sysctl kern.corefile`.\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** — use `lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app` to open the dump. For NativeAOT apps, since there's no managed runtime, `lldb` is the primary debugger (not `dotnet-dump`).\n\n6. **Symbolicate** — ensure your app was built with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`) so stack traces in `lldb` are meaningful.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"13db1b4d-f29c-49a2-8ae0-48ebf98cdc4a","outputTokens":332,"requestId":"784D:22A1A7:477E87:533395:69FA9E31"},"id":"237b39ff-31e1-4c8d-9918-573bec78f2a5","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:49:47.320Z","parentId":"ca52a0de-d4c1-4029-b8f1-b86252402216"}
